Age Rating Classification for Film Content

A Machine Learning Framework using IMDb Severity Metadata and YouTube Sentiment Signals


ğŸ“Œ Overview

This project builds an automated, scalable ageâ€“appropriateness prediction system for movies by combining structured severity annotations from the IMDb Parental Guide dataset with sentiment-derived severity signals from YouTube movie trailer comments.
Instead of relying on manual age-rating systems such as MPAA/BBFC, this project uses data-driven machine learning approaches to predict:
Severity codes for:
Sex & Nudity
Violence & Gore
Profanity
Drugs/Alcohol
Intense/Frightening Scenes
Final MPAA Rating (G, PG, PG-13, R, NC-17)
The framework is designed to be interpretable, reproducible, and cross-domain, aligning structured IMDb annotations with real-world audience sentiment.

ğŸ“‚ Datasets
1. IMDb Parental Guide Dataset (Training)
Contains ~49k movies with human-annotated severity levels across 5 categories.
Severity labels (None, Mild, Moderate, Severe) are encoded into 0â€“3.
Includes metadata such as runtime, votes, ratings, and certification.
2. YouTube Trailer Dataset (Testing)
Contains movie trailer URLs. Additional fields generated through scraping & analysis:
Top-20 user comments using yt-dlp
Video metadata (views, likes, publish date)
Sentiment polarity scores
Keyword-based content mentions (violence, profanity, drugs, etc.)
Sentiment distributions are automatically mapped to IMDb-like severity codes (0â€“3).

âš™ï¸ Methodology
Step 1 â€” IMDb Data Preprocessing

Encode severity labels
Standardize MPAA ratings (G â†’ NC-17)
Handle missing values
Log-transform skewed features (e.g., numVotes)
Minâ€“Max scaling
Apply SMOTE to address class imbalance

Step 2 â€” YouTube Comment Extraction & Sentiment Severity

Extract comments + metadata
Clean & preprocess text
Apply sentiment analysis
Convert aggregated sentiment â†’ severity levels
Align test dataset with IMDb schema

Step 3 â€” Model Training

A total of 12 machine learning models were trained:
Logistic Regression
Decision Tree
KNN
Random Forest
Gradient Boosting
XGBoost
LightGBM
CatBoost
Bagging
Voting Classifier
AdaBoost
MLP Neural Network
Hyperparameter tuning used GridSearchCV + 5-fold cross-validation.

Step 4 â€” Evaluation Metrics

Performance was measured using:
Accuracy
Precision, Recall
Weighted & Macro F1
ROCâ€“AUC Curves
Precisionâ€“Recall Curves
KS Statistic
Lift Analysis


ğŸ† Results
Best-performing model:
â­ Random Forest
Accuracy: 0.7759
Weighted F1: 0.7093
Other strong models: CatBoost, LightGBM, XGBoost, Bagging, Voting Classifier.
Weak models: AdaBoost, MLP (due to imbalance and noisy labels).


ğŸ“Š Visual Insights

The project includes rich EDA and diagnostic plots:
Severity distribution
Sentiment polarity distribution
Word clouds & keyword frequencies
ROCâ€“AUC curves
Precisionâ€“Recall curves
KS curves
Lift curves
These help understand severity co-occurrence, user sentiment patterns, and classifier separability.

ğŸ“ˆ Key Insights

Violence & Intense scenes show the highest correlation and have the strongest impact on MPAA prediction.
LightGBM shows the best class separability (highest KS).
Voting Classifier achieves near-perfect AUC in mid/high severity classes.
IMDb severity labels transfer well to YouTube sentiment-derived severity, validating cross-domain alignment.


ğŸš§ Challenges

Sparse high-severity categories (NC-17)
Sarcasm or vague YouTube comments lowering sentiment accuracy
Inconsistent content between trailers and full movies
Noise introduced in keyword-based comment mapping


ğŸ”® Future Work

Planned extensions include:
Transformer-based sentiment modeling (sarcasm, nuance, multi-label)
Vision models (ViT/CNN/LSTM) for scene-level severity estimation
Cross-regional certification (CBFC, OFLC, CHVRS)
Explainability (SHAP/LIME) for feature and phrase importance
Enhanced multi-label severity extraction from comments


